    "duration": 1.959999999999999,
    "scene_path": "videos/6qS83wD29PY/6qS83wD29PY_scenes/scene_006.mp4",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "text": "85 billion neurons.",
        "start": 0.0,
        "end": 1.0
      }
    ],
    "captions": []
  },
  {
    "scene_number": 7,
    "start_frame": 418,
    "end_frame": 487,
    "start_time": 16.72,
    "end_time": 19.48,
    "duration": 2.7600000000000016,
    "scene_path": "videos/6qS83wD29PY/6qS83wD29PY_scenes/scene_007.mp4",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "text": "The neuron is a nerve cell and it's the primary functional unit",
        "start": 0.0,
        "end": 2.62
      }
    ],
    "captions": []
  },
  {
    "scene_number": 8,
    "start_frame": 488,
    "end_frame": 596,
    "start_time": 19.52,
    "end_time": 23.84,
    "duration": 4.32,
    "scene_path": "videos/6qS83wD29PY/6qS83wD29PY_scenes/scene_008.mp4",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "text": "the nervous system. This is a generic image of a neuron. Neurons act",
        "start": 0.0,
        "end": 4.3
      }
    ],
    "captions": []
  },
  {
    "scene_number": 9,
    "start_frame": 597,
    "end_frame": 655,
    "start_time": 23.88,
    "end_time": 26.2,
    "duration": 2.3200000000000003,
    "scene_path": "videos/6qS83wD29PY/6qS83wD29PY_scenes/scene_009.mp4",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "text": "come in all shapes and sizes, but this is the prototypical",
        "start": 0.0,
        "end": 2.28
      }
    ],
    "captions": []
  },
  {
    "scene_number": 10,
    "start_frame": 656,
    "end_frame": 717,
    "start_time": 26.24,
    "end_time": 28.68,
    "duration": 2.4400000000000013,
    "scene_path": "videos/6qS83wD29PY/6qS83wD29PY_scenes/scene_010.mp4",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "text": "version of a neuron that you'll often see in a textbook.",
        "start": 0.0,
        "end": 1.94
      }
    ],
    "captions": []
  },
  {
    "scene_number": 11,
    "start_frame": 718,
    "end_frame": 853,
    "start_time": 28.72,
    "end_time": 34.12,
    "duration": 5.399999999999999,
    "scene_path": "videos/6qS83wD29PY/6qS83wD29PY_scenes/scene_011.mp4",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "text": "The structures extending from the left side of the neuron that look a little bit like tree branches are called dendrites.",
        "start": 0.75,
        "end": 5.39
      }
    ],
    "captions": []
  },
  {
    "scene_number": 12,
    "start_frame": 854,
    "end_frame": 953,
    "start_time": 34.16,
    "end_time": 38.12,
    "duration": 3.960000000000001,
    "scene_path": "videos/6qS83wD29PY/6qS83wD29PY_scenes/scene_012.mp4",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "text": "Dendrites are the area where neurons receive most of their information.",
        "start": 0.0,
        "end": 3.32
      }
    ],
    "captions": []
  },
  {
    "scene_number": 13,
    "start_frame": 954,
    "end_frame": 1293,
    "start_time": 38.16,
    "end_time": 51.72,
    "duration": 13.560000000000002,
    "scene_path": "videos/6qS83wD29PY/6qS83wD29PY_scenes/scene_013.mp4",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "text": "There are receptors on dendrites that are designed to pick up signals from other neurons that come in the form of chemicals called neurotransmitters.",
        "start": 0.0,
        "end": 6.34
      },
      {
        "text": "Those signals picked up by dendrites cause electrical changes in a neuron that are interpreted in an area called the soma, or the cell body.",
        "start": 6.74,
        "end": 13.54
      }
    ],
    "captions": []
  },
  {
    "scene_number": 14,
    "start_frame": 1294,
    "end_frame": 1381,
    "start_time": 51.76,
    "end_time": 55.24,
    "duration": 3.480000000000004,
    "scene_path": "videos/6qS83wD29PY/6qS83wD29PY_scenes/scene_014.mp4",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "text": "body. The soma contains the nucleus, which contains",
        "start": 0.0,
        "end": 3.26
      }
    ],
    "captions": []
  },
  {
    "scene_number": 15,
    "start_frame": 1382,
    "end_frame": 1590,
    "start_time": 55.28,
    "end_time": 63.6,
    "duration": 8.32,
    "scene_path": "videos/6qS83wD29PY/6qS83wD29PY_scenes/scene_015.mp4",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "text": "DNA or genetic material of the cell.",
        "start": 0.0,
        "end": 1.8
      },
      {
        "text": "The soma takes all the information from the dendrites and puts it together in an area",
        "start": 2.68,
        "end": 6.42
      },
      {
        "text": "called the axon hillock.",
        "start": 6.42,
        "end": 7.72
      }
    ],
    "captions": []
  },
  {
    "scene_number": 16,
    "start_frame": 1591,
    "end_frame": 1805,
    "start_time": 63.64,
    "end_time": 72.2,
    "duration": 8.560000000000002,
    "scene_path": "videos/6qS83wD29PY/6qS83wD29PY_scenes/scene_016.mp4",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "text": "If the signal coming from the dendrites is strong enough, then a signal is sent to the",
        "start": 0.21,
        "end": 4.21
      },
      {
        "text": "next part of the neuron, which is called the axon.",
        "start": 4.21,
        "end": 6.77
      },
      {
        "text": "at this point, the",
        "start": 7.4,
        "end": 8.4
      }
    ],
    "captions": []
  },
  {
    "scene_number": 17,
    "start_frame": 1806,
    "end_frame": 2029,
    "start_time": 72.24,
    "end_time": 81.16,
    "duration": 8.920000000000002,
    "scene_path": "videos/6qS83wD29PY/6qS83wD29PY_scenes/scene_017.mp4",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "text": "signal is called an action potential.",
        "start": 0.0,
        "end": 1.22
      },
      {
        "text": "The action potential travels down the axon, which is covered with myelin, an insulatory",
        "start": 2.51,
        "end": 7.23
      },
      {
        "text": "material that helps to prevent the signal from getting out of the axon.",
        "start": 7.23,
        "end": 9.01
      }
    ],
    "captions": []
  },
  {
    "scene_number": 18,
    "start_frame": 2030,
    "end_frame": 2597,
    "start_time": 81.2,
    "end_time": 103.88,
    "duration": 22.679999999999993,
    "scene_path": "videos/6qS83wD29PY/6qS83wD29PY_scenes/scene_018.mp4",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "text": "from degrading.",
        "start": 0.0,
        "end": 0.68
      },
      {
        "text": "The last step for the action potential is the axon terminals, also known as synaptic",
        "start": 1.79,
        "end": 6.33
      },
      {
        "text": "buttons.",
        "start": 6.33,
        "end": 6.61
      },
      {
        "text": "When the signal reaches the axon terminals, it can cause the release of neurotransmitter.",
        "start": 7.33,
        "end": 11.31
      },
      {
        "text": "These purple structures represent the dendrites of another neuron.",
        "start": 12.03,
        "end": 14.79
      },
      {
        "text": "When a neurotransmitter is released from axon terminals, it interacts with the receptors",
        "start": 15.19,
        "end": 18.77
      },
      {
        "text": "on the dendrites of the next neuron, and then the process repeats with the next neuron.",
        "start": 18.77,
        "end": 22.39
      }
    ],
    "captions": []
  },
